        "trailText":"<p>Heritage Classic at BC Place expands programme after 2012-13 lockout led to cancellation of all such showpiece games</p>",
        "headline":"Vancouver Canucks and Ottawa Senators to play outdoor NHL game",
        "body":"<p>The Vancouver Canucks will host the Ottawa Senators in a return of the Heritage Classic next season, the National Hockey League said on Wednesday. The game will be played on 2 March at BC Place, which was the venue for the opening ceremony of the 2010 Winter Olympics.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/jan/10/nhl-lockout-peace-deal-explained-bettman\">The 2012-13 NHL lockout</a> reduced the regular season to a 48-game schedule and meant no games were played outdoors. Perhaps partially as a result, an ambitious six-game outdoor programme for 2013-14 will kick off on New Year's Day with the Winter Classic between the Detroit Red Wings and the Toronto Maple Leafs at Michigan Stadium. The game is expected to attract a record NHL crowd of close to 110,000. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/nov/02/nhl-winter-classic-detroit-toronto\">The Winter Classic was scrapped last year</a>.</p><p>It will be followed by a four-game \"Stadium Series\", starting on 25 January with the Los Angeles Kings hosting the Anaheim Ducks at Dodger Stadium. The series will also include two games at Yankee Stadium, the New York Rangers facing the New Jersey Devils on 26 January and the New York Islanders on 29 January in the first hockey games to be played at the MLB stadium. The series will conclude on 1 March, when the Chicago Blackhawks – <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/jun/25/chicago-blackhawks-win-stanley-cup\">the Stanley Cup champions</a> – will host the Pittsburgh Penguins at Soldier Field, home of the NFL's Chicago Bears. </p><p>The Canucks will become the first NHL team to host a game in a facility with a retractable roof (which meant that BC Place was also the first <em>indoor</em> venue for an Olympic opening ceremony). The Heritage Classic is so named for the 1915 Stanley Cup championship, in which the Vancouver Millionaires swept a best-of-five series against the Ottawa Senators.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-cod