      "id":"sport/2013/jun/25/blackhawks-bruins-stanley-cup-best-moments",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-06-25T18:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Six magic moments as the Chicago Blackhawks won the Stanley Cup",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jun/25/blackhawks-bruins-stanley-cup-best-moments",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/jun/25/blackhawks-bruins-stanley-cup-best-moments",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Colin Horgan:</strong> From the Boston Bruins' dramatic comeback against the Toronto Maple Leafs to the triple overtime of Stanley Cup Final Game One, the 2013 NHL playoffs provided plenty of action</p>",
        "headline":"Six magic moments as the Chicago Blackhawks won the Stanley Cup",
        "body":"<p>After the disappointment of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/jan/10/nhl-lockout-peace-deal-explained-bettman\">a lockout-shortened regular season</a>, the 2013 NHL playoffs were full of great moments, upsets, hits and amazing goals. Among the highlights and low points, there were a handful of games that stood out. They were the ones that surprised, angered or just straight out dazzled. Here are six of them:</p><h2>Bruins-Leafs Game Seven</h2><p>The final series between the Bruins and the Blackhawks might have been a classic, but it's fair to say the hockey world will also be talking about this first round Game Seven for just as long. There are collapses, and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/may/16/toronto-maple-leafs-nhl-playoffs-bruins\">then there are the 2013 Toronto Maple Leafs</a>, who inadvertently gave everyone a clinic on how to blow a Game Seven lead like they were making way for a runaway freight train – which, as it turned out, they were, given how the Boston Bruins morphed from a Maybe team into a definite threat in the following two rounds. <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XdvoDFTcTLw&amp;feature=youtu.be\">Here's how it happened</a>:</p><p><em></em></p><p>The Leafs fell 5-4 in overtime, and the 2013 playoff Bruins were born – a monster that ate everything it its path until hitting the Blackhawks in the final round. </p><p><a href=\"http://youtu.be/u8GCH5qf9IY\">These Leafs fans even allowed us into their personal grief</a>:</p><p><em></em></p><h2>Penguins-Islanders Game Two</h2><p>Hindsight is 20/20, but maybe this is where we really should have started thinking the Pittsburgh Penguins had some problems – bad enough to prevent them from winning the Cup they seemed so capable of grabbing this year. The New York Islanders, who scraped their way into the post-season, surprised the Penguins at home, winning Game Two in regulation 4-3. That it proved not to be a one-off (they repeated the split back home on Long Island a few days later, racking up 6 goals against the Pens) equally signaled that the Iles might have some potential for next year.</p><p><a href=\"http://youtu.be/59pZaY_rLes\">Here's Kyle Okposo's winner that night.</a></p><h2>Senators-Canadiens Game Three</h2><p>Though this matchup didn't quite pan out as probably most fans in Montreal and Ottawa might have hoped (long series, close games), the rivalry between the two teams certainly heated up. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/may/06/senators-canadiens-line-brawl-fighting-penalty\">Game Three</a> helped that – a lot. The rest of the series was physical, but following a hit that left Habs forward Lars Eller concussed and bleeding on the ice in Montreal, the animosity rose to peak levels back in Ottawa in the third period of Game Three, with the Senators up 4-1. The Habs had had enough, and the Senators were happy to oblige. <a href=\"http://youtu.be/oAQtabmrV7Q\">Everyone lost their cool</a>:</p><p><em></em></p><p>Maybe it was what everyone needed to cool off. The next time the two sides met in Game Four, things were still physical, but decidedly calmer. That one was even much closer, with the Senators only managing to take it in overtime against Montreal's backup goaltender, Peter Budaj. </p><h2>Sharks-Kings Game Two</h2><p>The second game between state rivals San Jose and L.A. was looking very much like it would go to the Sharks and give them the road split and the momentum heading back to San Jose for Game Three. Leading 3-1 with only minutes left in the third, things looked wrapped up. But then Dustin Brown, captain of the Stanley Cup holders, popped one past Antti Niemi to tie it with just 1:43 left in the third, and two Sharks in the box. Then, with about a minute left in both the powerplay and the game, <a href=\"http://youtu.be/eWWNQYQeCRg\">Trevor Lewis sealed it for the Kings</a>. </p><p>Afterwards, <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2013/05/17/nhl_playoffs_2013_la_kings_come_back_to_stun_san_jose_sharks_in_game_2.html\">Lewis said</a>:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>\"I almost passed out on the celebration. I got a little light-headed. To score a big goal in the playoffs is what you dream about.\"</p></blockquote><h2>Blackhawks-Kings Game Five </h2><p>In what proved to be something of a preview of the final round, the last game between Chicago and LA in the Western conference final went to double-overtime and the ever-productive <a href=\"http://youtu.be/zCs0-4yn3Mg\">Patrick Kane banged home the winner for the Blackhawks</a> – his third of the night – off a precision pass from captain Jonathan Toews. It was LA's last gasp, a team that had started to look more dangerous each round, aiming for a repeat Cup win, but missing at least one key man (Mike Richards) and staring down a fast, deep Chicago squad. Looking back now, the fact that it took the Blackhawks a couple games in the final to reunite Toews and Kane on the first line remains an even deeper mystery. </p><h2>Blackhawks-Bruins Game One</h2><p>Triple overtime. The fifth-longest game in NHL playoff history. One-hundred and seventeen shots in total. One-hundred and twenty hits between the two teams. Sixty-three blocked shots. Fifty-two extra minutes. And then <a href=\"http://youtu.be/xccbuJ_jzLk\">this</a>:</p><p><em></em></p><p>And, amazingly, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/jun/25/chicago-blackhawks-win-stanley-cup\">it got even better from there on</a>.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/411486178|2013-10-07T10:05:52Z|74cc22a5b32587bdb5735de18d9bb5cdae627db5 -->",
