      "id":"sport/2013/apr/23/tyler-seguin-bruins-no-homo-twitter",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-04-23T14:05:27Z",
      "webTitle":"Bruins' Tyler Seguin puts NHL's homophobia clampdown to the test",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/apr/23/tyler-seguin-bruins-no-homo-twitter",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/apr/23/tyler-seguin-bruins-no-homo-twitter",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Colin Horgan:</strong> Boston Bruins' Tyler Seguin tweets homophobic comment; NHL announces Winter Classic expansion; Edmonton Oilers shuffle deckchairs</p>",
        "headline":"Bruins' Tyler Seguin puts NHL's homophobia clampdown to the test",
        "body":"<h2>&quot;No homo&quot; says Tyler Seguin</h2><p>Just over a week after <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/apr/12/nhl-you-can-play-gay-homophobia\">the NHL signed on officially as a partner with You Can Play</a>, the organization founded to help reduce LGBT stigmatization in sports, Bruins forward Tyler Seguin tweeted about a rap song by Boston artist Slaine, called &quot;<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4z0UGCKqNAY\">Nothin' But Business</a>&quot;. Seguin told the world (in <a href=\"http://twitter.com/FlandersBreivik/status/326530116488421378/photo/1\">a now deleted tweet</a>): </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>&quot;Just listened to the song in my bed. Gave me goosebumps no homo. My roommate and boy have some skills @freddybender @KnucklesNBS&quot;. </p></blockquote><p>Seguin must have realized his mistake pretty quickly (no doubt a few Twitter users let him know) and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/tylerseguin92/status/326534197915316225\">tweeted an apology</a>: &quot;You know when your half asleep and say or write something without thinking twice or realizing what you said. Apologies on last tweet. Gnight.&quot; </p><p>You Can Play founder Patrick Burke retweeted that message after <a href=\"http://twitter.com/BurkieYCP/status/326532660358959104\">making sure everyone knew what was wrong with it</a>, followed by a call for calm. &quot;Is it the end of the world?&quot; <a href=\"http://twitter.com/BurkieYCP/status/326532986050846721\">he asked Twitter</a>. &quot;No. And I'm sure he's already regretting it. All that's going to happen is some education from us. No discipline.&quot; Then, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/BurkieYCP/status/326533310903906304\">Burke wrote</a>: &quot;Deep breaths on both 'sides' of my twitter feed for be helpful. It's not acceptable for him to say that, but he's not a monster for it.&quot;</p><p><em></em></p><p>Probably Seguin didn't mean much by the comment, but that in itself is part of the problem. Does he deserve any discipline other than a stern reminder from someone that it's not acceptable? I'm betting he got a pretty good one from the Twitterverse on Monday.</p><h2>How the NHL is ruining the outdoor game</h2><p>One of the first fatalities of last fall's lockout was the Winter Classic scheduled between Detroit and Toronto, slated to be played at Michigan Stadium in Ann Arbour. Thankfully, that game's been resurrected – to the point where we already know the jerseys the teams will be wearing (which are great). But it looks like perhaps the league is overcompensating a bit. This week <a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/story/2013/04/16/sp-nhl-outdoor-games-stadium-series-heritage-classic.html\">it announced</a> there will be five more outdoor games next year. Five. More.</p><p>Or, to put it another way, the NHL discovered a goldmine of ratings, revenues and national attention and, like any the worst kind of greedy, cartoonish cohort of cash-grab artists, saw only dollar signs, and thus set about systematically bleeding that mine to death. </p><p>Granted most of the list is good, apart from one obvious joke. The games will include a meeting between the L.A. Kings and Anaheim Ducks at Dodger Stadium (LOL); the Rangers against both the Islanders and Devils respectively – both at Yankee Stadium; the Penguins meeting the Blackhawks at Soldier Field in Chicago; and the Senators and Canucks facing off at B.C. Place in Vancouver. I've personally never been aware of a storied rivalry of any kind between the 'Nucks and the Sens, (if you have, leave a comment), but fine – they needed another Canadian one for balance. But why not spread these games out over years, rather than a couple of months?</p><p>On the plus side, past Winter Classics have been well-attended and a nice way to mark the new year with a mid-season marquee event right at the time (winter, that is) where it makes the most sense to remember the best elements of the game and its history. And, most importantly, people seem to love them.</p><p>They also make a lot of money. Those aforementioned special jerseys being only the start. <a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/story/2013/04/20/sp-nhl-hotstove-outdoor-games-will-generate-big-revenue.html\">Elliotte Friedman noted as much on Hockey Night in Canada</a> this weekend: &quot;These games are worth about $30 million US a piece and the cap is going down next year. I think there's a big concern among players,&quot; he said. &quot;So if it's an extra $180 million, it's $90 million for the league and $90 million for the players, and I think that's a very big factor [that] all of these games are going to happen.&quot;</p><p>And then there are the detractors, who recognize all of those good things and yet rationally question the excess.</p><p>Friedman (via TSN's Darren Dreger) points to another problem with this set of games: They fall soon after the players arrive back from the Olympics, in particular the final two – Pittsburgh vs. Chicago on March 1 and Ottawa vs. Vancouver on March 2. <a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/opinion/2013/04/6-outdoor-nhl-games-too-much-for-players.html\">He writes</a>:</p><blockquote><p>&quot;That's six and seven days, respectively, after the conclusion of the Sochi Olympics. Look at the rosters of those four teams. Things can change, but how many players are going to Russia? You could make a good argument for at least 30. It seems overly risky to send those players halfway across the world, bring them back and thrust them into unfamiliar surroundings.&quot;</p></blockquote><p>Both <a href=\"http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/nhl-outdoor-stadium-series-why-bad-idea-162250998--nhl.html?utm_source=twitterfeed&amp;utm_medium=twitter\">Harrison Mooney at Puck Daddy and Eric Duhatschek at the Globe and Mail</a> point to another potential issues: effectively demoting what was once a special event into a mundane oh-this-again happening that everyone just starts to despise.</p><p>&quot;Six outdoor games dilutes the brand by eroding the specialness of the Winter Classic, but not just by flooding the market with similar, less special events to follow it,&quot; Mooney writes. &quot;It's also the way that it underscores the cynical cash-grab aspects of the whole thing.&quot;</p><p>And how important is that money, in the long run?</p><p>&quot;It just makes more sense to keep it as a special event, something you can point to annually on the hockey calendar and say, 'gotta set aside time for that.' The minute it becomes a choice of six, then suddenly, the dilution starts – and who knows where it could end?,&quot; <a href=\"http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/duhatschek-additional-outdoor-games-are-too-much-of-a-good-thing/article11359730/\">Duhatschek writes</a>. &quot;The NHL just might be killing its golden goose.&quot;</p><p>And how. There's not only a risk of total market saturation to a point of total destruction, but even worse, it feels like a gimmick. And the only thing worse than feeling like you're being asked to pay for a gimmick, is feeling like you're being asked to pay for a gimmick that's disguised as a premium add-on – kind of like those extended warranties at an electronics store. If it's no longer actually special, people won't bother giving it any special attention.</p><p>Even worse than simply mining this concept for all the money and ratings the NHL can pump out of it? Now all the fun will be gone, too. Part of what was so special about the winter games was that they were rare, in amazing places, and everyone was left to speculate on where the next one might be, who might play, and on the possible venues. That was part of what made them fun and something to look forward to all year. Now, with six scheduled for 2014, it looks more and more like, eventually, everyone will get a Winter Classic. Which is fine, but it's just no longer a marquee game. For a league with so few opportunities to grab everyone's attention like that, it seems a waste. Hope the money's worth it.</p><h2>The Oilers are a mess, basically</h2><p>And now, for the inevitable change of management in Edmonton. Or rather, a shuffling of the deckchairs. <a href=\"http://sports.nationalpost.com/2013/04/15/oilers-fire-general-manager-steve-tambellini-report/\">The Oilers announced </a>that general manager Steve Tambellini is out, and the organization is replacing him with... former Oilers head coach Craig MacTavish, the guy Tambellini fired the first day he took the GM job in 2009. Granted, MacTavish was the man who was last coaching the Oilers when they had a legitimate shot at a Cup (2006), but with a talented, but perpetually unproductive team, this is probably not really the kind of change that's likely necessary in Edmonton. </p><p>The whole thing was made even worse by the fact that Kevin Lowe, the team's president of hockey operations, managed to insult fans while announcing the change. He noted that the Oilers have &quot;two types of fans: we have paying customers and we have people that watch the game that we still care about. But certainly the people that go to the games and support we spend a lot of time talking to them, delivering our message.&quot; </p><p>The comment – essentially interpreted as Lowe cutting a line down the middle of the fans, splicing them into two groups based on disposable income – was quickly (and probably rightly) <a href=\"http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Edmonton/2013/04/15/20743461.html\">decried, blown out of proportion, and Twitter-shamed</a>. Lowe issued a video apology:</p><p><em></em></p><p>But as <a href=\"http://sports.nationalpost.com/2013/04/19/anger-at-kevin-lowe-a-sign-oilers-fans-are-growing-impatient/\">Cam Cole pointed out this week at the National Post</a>, Lowe was really only speaking the truth: It's the stadium-goers that really bring home the bacon. He notes that for a family of four to go to a game in Edmonton, &quot;and eat a little and drink a little and park, and maybe buy a ball cap, etc&quot; is C$346.46. The fans that stay at home? They pay for cable. Maybe they buy a jersey from time to time. Lowe didn't say anything outrageous. Instead, it all had to do with timing, Cole argues.</p><blockquote><p>&quot;The thing he missed is that the maelstrom of angry responses to his message of the day before was only a little bit about his dividing the Oiler fan base into tiers of importance. It was mostly about the public's general impatience, and its growing exasperation with what it perceives as his get-out-of-jail-free card.</p><p>He could have said anything, if his hockey club was winning.&quot;</p></blockquote><p>Yeah. <a href=\"http://www.nhl.com/ice/standings.htm\">About that...</a></p><h2>Kiprusoff's last dance?</h2><p>This is a weird year for Calgary and its fans. All those changes fans had hoped might take place are indeed happening, but the perhaps is somewhat surprising. After the trade deadline passed and Mikka Kiprusoff stayed in Calgary, it was only a matter of time before he called it quits. But now, with Iginla and now Kiprusoff having just played what was likely his last game at the Saddledome this week, the final remnants of that 2004 glory season are gone. Perhaps not a moment too soon, but there's something a bit bittersweet about the whole thing. </p><p><a href=\"http://youtu.be/FNolVdy_z-k\">The fans in Calgary obliged him with a final standing ovation</a>.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.calgaryherald.com/sports/hockey/calgary-flames/Kipper+realizes+childhood+dream+gets+with/8274683/story.html\">As Puck Daddy noted</a>, most disappointed of all will likely be <a href=\"http://youtu.be/D61TyprHVY8\">&quot;Kipper Kid&quot; (aka Brendan Peters), who for a time was known in Calgary simply as the child who stood behind Kiprusoff during warm-ups dressed in exactly the same gear as the Flames goalie, and mimicked his every move</a>. Peters is now in high school, and has basically moved on with his life. Hopefully, unlike their rivals to the north, the Flames organization is ready to truly do the same.</p><h2>Sharks fan cries, meets Sharks, scolds Sharks</h2><p>Speaking of small children who are obsessed with hockey, a final, quick point about a viral video. When Ryan Clowe was traded to New York, seven-year-old Sharks fan Vincent Savage was overcome with sadness. So profound was his depression, he wandered into his back yard and had a good cry. And, like all parents these days, hoping to capture that precious moment for all the internet to see, <a href=\"http://youtu.be/2Ux84k2XWPE\">his mother recorded it:</a></p><p>To his credit, Savage raises a great, often wrenching, question that sports fans have to deal with all the time. When a favourite player moves on from a favourite team, what happens? Do you automatically become a fan of their new team, even if there was no prior affiliation? How do you still cheer for your preferred squad when there's such an emptiness left by the departed star? Poor Savage. Life never really gets easier, does it?</p><p>In any case, the Sharks saw it (noting, probably, Savage's apparent newfound anger at the club), and tried to make amends: the team invited him to visit the locker room after a pre-game skate. But, <a href=\"http://www.mercurynews.com/sharks/ci_23054546/san-jose-sharks-try-patch-things-up-angry\">according to reports</a>, it might not have actually done much good. Savage reportedly told them all that &quot;I can't believe you haven't won any Stanley Cups.&quot; When he was corrected that, actually, Dan Boyle had, he then replied, &quot;but you haven't won one with the Sharks.&quot; Perpetually unimpressed. I like it.</p><h2>Goals of the week</h2><p><em></em></p><h2><a href=\"http://www.nhl.com/ice/standings.htm\">NHL standings</a></h2><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/407696915|2013-10-07T10:05:52Z|21043788eafa747754599f1becd68b12aa73080a -->",
